  "doc_id": "20495",
  "text": "Four hundred and ten HIV-infected patients (352 men and 58 women, age range: 28-65 years) were recruited at 43 sites between June 2005 and April 2006 to participate in a 26-week placebo-controlled Phase 3 trial to assess the efficacy and safety of tesamorelin in reducing VAT [CITATION_1] . Patients were randomly assigned in a ratio of 2 : 1 to receive either 2 mg of tesamorelin or matching placebo, administered by subcutaneous injection, for 26 weeks. At 26 weeks, patients initially in the tesamorelin group were re-randomized to either continue tesamorelin (T-T group, N ¼ 154) or receive placebo (T-P group, N ¼ 50) from week 26 to 52. Body composition and metabolic endpoints from this extension phase, including information on CRP and adiponectin, but not tPA antigen or PAI-1 antigen, were previously published [CITATION_2] .",
